l Twist]], the late [[XXXTentacion]] and [[O.T. Genasis]]. \"I Do It\" featuring Big Sean and Lil Baby was released as a single the same day as the album.<ref>{{Cite tweet|url=https://twitter.com/LilTunechi/status/1223495272044679168?s=19|title=The new single I Do It ft. @BigSean & @lilbaby4PF off #Funeral is now available...|date=January 31, 2020|website=[[Twitter]]|access-date=February 27, 2020|user=LilTunechi|author=Lil Wayne|number=1223495272044679168}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn 2016, while Lil Wayne was in the midst of the legal battle with [[Cash Money Records]] over contractual disputes, it was announced that his next album would be titled ''Funeral''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/11/lil-waynes-new-funeral-project-on-the-way/|title=Lil Wayne's New 'Funeral' Project Is on the Way \u2013 XXL}}</ref> The album was completed in 2019, as Wayne started promoting the album again.<ref>{{cite web |title=Is Lil Wayne teasing his Funeral album again? |url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/04/30/lil-wayne-funeral-album-tease-2019-instagram-story |website=The Fader |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Everything We Know About Lil Wayne's New Album 'Funeral' |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/01/lil-wayne-new-album-funeral-everything-we-know/ |website=Complex |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'', Lil Wayne spoke on how his recording process changed throughout his career, saying:\n{{quote|I love the difficulty of trying to fit in with what's going on today, making sure I sound likeable to the ears today and having to remind myself that it's not about what it was back then. [\u2026] I can't wait to get in the studio now every night, just to see what I can come up with. [Before] it was just me going to the studio and saying, let me kill ten more songs and then I'm going to go home or do whatever I was doing. Now, it's let me see what I come up with. Self-discovery, rebirth \u2013 call it whatever you want to call it but it feels awesome, I swear to God.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lil Wayne Talks 'Ghost Recon Breakpoint' Game, 'Funeral' Sessions And More |url=https://www.vibe.com/2019/09/lil-wayne-talks-ghost-recon-breakpoint-game-funeral-sessions-and-more |website=Vibe |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nLil Wayne explained the title ''Funeral'' as a continuation of his album ''[[Rebirth (Lil Wayne album)|Rebirth]]'' in 2010, to follow-up on the series.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Marcus |title=Lil Wayne talks new album Funeral: 'If my real funeral was tomorrow, it's still not my last album' |url=https://ew.com/music/2020/01/31/lil-wayne-funeral-album-interview/ |website=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=First Impressions of Lil Wayne's New Album 'Funeral' |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/01/lil-wayne-new-album-funeral-first-impressions |website=Complex |accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Album cover==\nThe calligraphic text on the [[Album cover|cover]] features a rotational [[ambigram]]. It reads ''Funeral'' right side up and ''Lil Wayne'' upside down.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Lil Wayne releases his 13th album, Funeral |url=https://ew.com/music/2020/01/31/lil-wayne-releases-13th-album-funeral/ |website=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\nOn January 23, 2020, Lil Wayne revealed the album's release date and artwork.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lil Wayne to Drop New Album Funeral Next Friday |url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2020/01/lil-wayne-funeral-album-release-date/ |website=XXL |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> With the announcement, he also teased a snippet of the album with lyrics \"welcome to the funeral, closed casket as usual.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Lil Wayne Details New Album 'Funeral' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-wayne-new-album-funeral-942396/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lil Wayne Releasing New Album Funeral Next Week |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lil-wayne-announces-new-album-teases-new-music-listen/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lil Wayne Previews \"Funeral\" Song With Russell Westbrook Shoutout |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-wayne-previews-funeral-song-with-russell-westbrook-shoutout-news.102383.html |website=HotNewHipHop |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 62/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/funeral/lil-wayne|title=Funeral by Lil Wayne Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 4, 2020|archive-url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/funeral/lil-wayne|archive-date=February 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| ADM = 5.9/10<ref name=\"AnyDecentMusic\">{{cite web|title=Funeral by Lil Wayne Reviews|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/10242/Lil-Wayne-Funeral.aspx|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=February 4, 2020|archive-url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/10242/Lil-Wayne-Funeral.aspx|archive-date=February 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev1score = B-<ref name=\"Consequence of Sound\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/album-review-lil-wayne-funeral/|title=Lil Wayne's Funeral Celebrates a Life That's Far from Over|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Thiessen|first=Christopher|date=February 3, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev2score = 6.0/10<ref name=\"Exclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/lil_wayne-funeral|title=Lil Wayne Funeral|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Carey|first=Jacob|date=February 3, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020|archive-url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/lil_wayne-funeral|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/lil-wayne-funeral-review-the-big-kid-2604385|title=Lil Wayne \u2013 'Funeral' review: the big kid refuses to grow up on this fitfully inspired surprise release|work=[[NME]]|last=Hobbs|first=Thomas|date=February 3, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020|archive-url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/lil-wayne-funeral-review-the-big-kid-2604385|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev4score = 7.3/10<ref name=Pitchfork>{{cite web|last=Pearce|first=Sheldon|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/lil-wayne-funeral/|title=Lil Wayne: Funeral|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/lil-wayne-funeral-946939/|title=Lil Wayne Displays Moments of Genius on the Wildly Uneven 'Funeral'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Schwartz|first=Danny|date=February 3, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020|archive-url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/lil-wayne-funeral-946939/|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|last=Empire|first=Kitty|authorlink=Kitty Empire|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/feb/09/lil-wayne-funeral-review|title=Lil Wayne: Funeral review \u2013 fearsome and full of life|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=February 9, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/feb/09/lil-wayne-funeral-review|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Funeral'' was met with positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 62, based on nine reviews.<ref>{{Citation|title=Funeral by Lil Wayne|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/funeral/lil-wayne|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave it 5.9 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/10242/Lil-Wayne-Funeral.aspx|title=Funeral by Lil Wayne reviews {{!}} Any Decent Music|website=www.anydecentmusic.com|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn a mixed review, Christopher Thiessen of [[Consequence of Sound|''Consequence of Sound'']] wrote: \"''Funeral'' plays less like an album and more like a mixtape. For his new decade debut, Wayne takes a 'throw everything at the wall and see what sticks' approach, only hitting the target about half the time. Wayne is at his best when he dives into a beat and shows off his technical skill. He still has endless punchlines to punctuate his effortless flow. He still has clear vision and awareness of his place in the hip-hop game. However, Wayne is not a great editor, and thus listening to ''Funeral'' can become exhausting about halfway through. While listeners may be fatigued, however, Wayne is far from it. ''Funeral'' isn't an ending point or a period at the end of a successful career. It's an ellipsis, a thought to be continued next time Weezy graces the studio\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/album-review-lil-wayne-funeral/|title=Album Review: Lil Wayne's Funeral Celebrates a Life That's Far from Over|date=February 3, 2020|website=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> Jacob Carey of ''[[Exclaim!]]'' criticized the length of the album, stating: \"While ''Funeral'' isn't necessarily a flop, the album would have ranked higher in Lil Wayne's discography had he cut the tracklist in half and opted for quality over quantity. Overall, ''Funeral'' lacks replay value compared to the multiple 'best of the year' albums that Wayne has proven capable of creating.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/lil_wayne-funeral|title=Lil Wayne Funeral|website=exclaim.ca|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[NME]]'''s Thomas Hobbs found the album inconsistent, writing: \"The problem with ''Funeral'' is that there's no real thread holding the music together. For every exhilarating left turn ('Mama Mia' was made to open up the mosh pits), there's a soulless radio anthem such as 'Clap For Em' \u2013 and that's before we even mention the unspeakable [[Adam Levine]] duet 'Trust Nobody'. At nearly 80 minutes long, ''Funeral'' is obviously bloated and an attempt to play into streaming politics, and it's a real shame that the ambitious druggy swirl of some of the earlier material is replaced with more formulaic songwriting\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/lil-wayne-funeral-review-the-big-kid-2604385|title=Lil Wayne \u2013 'Funeral' review|date=February 2, 2020|website=NME||accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\nDanny Schwartz of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the album a negative review, saying \"''Funeral'' is wildly uneven, a landscape of pronounced highs and lows. In truth, it peaks early, on 'Mahogany'.\" Schwartz called \"Trust Nobody\" the worst song on the album, labeling it a \"sunk by a banal and out-of-place Adam Levine hook, while noting that \"Get Out Of My Head\" is \"soured by the great rap pedant [[XXXTentacion]]\" and called \"Sights and Silencers\" a \"surprisingly limp [[The-Dream]] ballad that he should have just given to [[Jeremih]]\". Schwartz concluded: \"''Funeral'' is pockmarked with [[Dud|duds]] [...]  Lil Wayne's previous album, ''[[Tha Carter V]]'', was also overlong, but it was at least anchored by a gentle familial undercurrent. Aside from a few moments, like 'Bastard (Satan's Kid)' which touches on Wayne's father's neglectful parenting, ''Funeral'' is emotionally adrift. As Wayne heads into a new decade\u2014his fourth as a professional rapper\u2014it's hard to [know] where his head is at, where he's coming from, or where he's going\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/lil-wayne-funeral-946939/|title=Lil Wayne Displays Moments of Genius on the Wildly Uneven 'Funeral'|last=Schwartz|first=Danny|date=February 3, 2020|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConversely, [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']]'s Sheldon Pearce gave an overall positive review, saying \"Weezy is back in the booth and cruising, experimenting with an array of styles and a dizzying maze of wordplay\".<ref name=\"Pitchfork\" /> Furthermore, writing for [[The Guardian|''The Guardian'']], Kitty Empire gave the album a positive review, saying \"Wayne's unheralded 13th studio album proves that the 37-year-old's flow can still be fearsome, even if his edit function remains iffy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/feb/09/lil-wayne-funeral-review|title=Lil Wayne: Funeral review \u2013 fearsome and full of life|last=Empire|first=Kitty|date=February 9, 2020|website=The Guardian|accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Funeral'' debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] dated February 15, 2020, with 139,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, of which 38,000 were pure album sales. It is Lil Wayne's fifth US number-one album.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8550510/lil-wayne-funeral-fifth-no-1-billboard-200-album-chart|title=Lil Wayne Achieves Fifth No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Funeral'|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=February 9, 2020|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/129866889|title=Funeral / Lil Wayne|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length